We use the symmetric measure Adjusted Mutual Information (AMI)32 to measure the similarity between the group-level and an individual-level modularization. The AMI is an extension to Mutual Information (MI) score and accounts for the chance. We avoid using MI and normalized MI (NMI) since they increase for two partitions with high number of modules, irrespective of the information shared33. Similarly, we also avoid using Adjusted Rand Index since it is preferred for modularizations with large similarly sized modules34, whereas brain modules are non-uniformly sized35. The AMI between two modularizations \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
